\title{Analyzing Ios App Security With Objection}

\taxon{skill}

\tag{mobile-security}

\tag{ios}

\tag{objection}

\tag{frida}

\tag{owasp-mobile}

\tag{penetration-testing}

\meta{version}{1.0.0}

\meta{description}{Performs runtime mobile security exploration of iOS applications using Objection, a Frida-powered toolkit that enables security testers to interact with app internals without jailbreaking. Use when assessing iOS app security posture, bypassing client-side protections, dumping keychain items, inspecting filesystem storage, and evaluating runtime behavior. Activates for requests involving iOS security testing, Objection runtime analysis, Frida-based iOS assessment, or mobile runtime exploration.}

\subtree{
\title{Analyzing iOS App Security with Objection}
\subtree{
\title{When to Use}
\p{Use this skill when:}

\ul{
\li{Performing runtime security assessment of iOS applications during authorized penetration tests}
\li{Inspecting iOS keychain, filesystem, and memory for sensitive data exposure}
\li{Bypassing client-side security controls (SSL pinning, jailbreak detection) during security testing}
\li{Evaluating iOS app behavior at runtime without access to source code}
}

\p{\strong{Do not use} this skill on production devices without explicit authorization -- Objection modifies app runtime behavior and may trigger security monitoring.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Prerequisites}
\ul{
\li{Python 3.10+ with pip}
\li{Objection installed: \code{\startverb pip install objection\stopverb}}
\li{Frida installed: \code{\startverb pip install frida-tools\stopverb}}
\li{Target iOS device (jailbroken with Frida server, or non-jailbroken with repackaged IPA)}
\li{For non-jailbroken: \code{\startverb objection patchipa\stopverb} to inject Frida gadget into IPA}
\li{macOS recommended for iOS testing (Xcode, ideviceinstaller)}
\li{USB connection to target device or network Frida server}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Workflow}
\subtree{
\title{Step 1: Prepare the Testing Environment}
\p{\strong{For jailbroken devices:}}

\pre{\startverb
# Install Frida server on device via Cydia/Sileo
# SSH to device and start Frida server
ssh root@<device_ip> "/usr/sbin/frida-server -D"

# Verify Frida connectivity
frida-ps -U  # List processes on USB-connected device
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{For non-jailbroken devices (authorized testing):}}

\pre{\startverb
# Patch IPA with Frida gadget
objection patchipa --source target.ipa --codesign-signature "Apple Development: test@example.com"

# Install patched IPA
ideviceinstaller -i target-patched.ipa
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 2: Attach Objection to Target App}
\pre{\startverb
# Attach to running app by bundle ID
objection --gadget "com.target.app" explore

# Or spawn the app fresh
objection --gadget "com.target.app" explore --startup-command "ios hooking list classes"
\stopverb}

\p{Once attached, Objection provides an interactive REPL for runtime exploration.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 3: Assess Data Storage Security (MASVS-STORAGE)}
\pre{\startverb
# Dump iOS Keychain items accessible to the app
ios keychain dump

# List files in app sandbox
ios plist cat Info.plist
env  # Show app environment paths

# Inspect NSUserDefaults for sensitive data
ios nsuserdefaults get

# List SQLite databases
sqlite connect app_data.db
sqlite execute query "SELECT * FROM credentials"

# Check for sensitive data in pasteboard
ios pasteboard monitor
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 4: Evaluate Network Security (MASVS-NETWORK)}
\pre{\startverb
# Disable SSL/TLS certificate pinning
ios sslpinning disable

# Verify pinning is bypassed by observing traffic in Burp Suite proxy
# Monitor network-related class method calls
ios hooking watch class NSURLSession
ios hooking watch class NSURLConnection
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 5: Inspect Authentication and Authorization (MASVS-AUTH)}
\pre{\startverb
# List all Objective-C classes
ios hooking list classes

# Search for authentication-related classes
ios hooking search classes Auth
ios hooking search classes Login
ios hooking search classes Token

# Hook authentication methods to observe parameters
ios hooking watch method "+[AuthManager validateToken:]" --dump-args --dump-return

# Monitor biometric authentication calls
ios hooking watch class LAContext
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 6: Assess Binary Protections (MASVS-RESILIENCE)}
\pre{\startverb
# Check jailbreak detection implementation
ios jailbreak disable

# Simulate jailbreak detection bypass
ios jailbreak simulate

# List loaded frameworks and libraries
memory list modules

# Search memory for sensitive strings
memory search "password" --string
memory search "api_key" --string
memory search "Bearer" --string

# Dump specific memory regions
memory dump all dump_output/
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 7: Review Platform Interaction (MASVS-PLATFORM)}
\pre{\startverb
# List URL schemes registered by the app
ios info binary
ios bundles list_frameworks

# Hook URL scheme handlers
ios hooking watch method "-[AppDelegate application:openURL:options:]" --dump-args

# Monitor clipboard access
ios pasteboard monitor

# Check for custom keyboard restrictions
ios hooking search classes UITextField
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Key Concepts}
\pre{\startverb
| Term | Definition |
|------|-----------|
| **Objection** | Runtime mobile exploration toolkit built on Frida that provides pre-built scripts for common security testing tasks |
| **Frida Gadget** | Shared library injected into app process to enable Frida instrumentation without jailbreak |
| **Keychain** | iOS secure credential storage system; Objection can dump items accessible to the target app's keychain access group |
| **SSL Pinning Bypass** | Runtime modification of certificate validation logic to allow proxy interception of HTTPS traffic |
| **Method Hooking** | Intercepting Objective-C/Swift method calls at runtime to observe arguments, return values, and modify behavior |
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Tools & Systems}
\ul{
\li{\strong{Objection}: High-level Frida-powered mobile security exploration toolkit with pre-built commands}
\li{\strong{Frida}: Dynamic instrumentation framework providing JavaScript injection into native app processes}
\li{\strong{Frida-tools}: CLI utilities for Frida including frida-ps, frida-trace, and frida-discover}
\li{\strong{ideviceinstaller}: Cross-platform tool for installing/managing iOS apps via USB}
\li{\strong{Burp Suite}: HTTP proxy for intercepting traffic after SSL pinning bypass}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Common Pitfalls}
\ul{
\li{\strong{App crashes on attach}: Some apps implement Frida detection. Use \code{\startverb --startup-command\stopverb} to hook anti-Frida checks early in the app lifecycle.}
\li{\strong{Keychain access scope}: Objection can only dump keychain items within the app's access group. System keychain items require separate jailbreak-level tools.}
\li{\strong{Swift name mangling}: Swift method names are mangled in the runtime. Use \code{\startverb ios hooking list classes\stopverb} with grep to find demangled names.}
\li{\strong{Non-persistent changes}: All Objection modifications are runtime-only and reset on app restart. Document findings immediately.}
}
}
}